Getting Data

There are 2 ways to get data:

  • Web Scraping
    • Fully Customizable
    • Potentially Difficult
    • Frequent Monitoring and Rebuilding
    • Security Risks?
  • Web Aggregators
    • User-Friendly APIs
    • Limited Data Sources
    • Money?
    • Security Risks?

Web Scraping Example

Step 2: Find URLs of Specific Press Releases

press.list<-list()
for(i in 1:length(page.list)){
  page<-read_html(page.list[i])
  sections <- page %>%
    html_nodes("h2")
  websites <- as.vector(xpathSApply(htmlParse(sections), "//a/@href"))
  press.list[[i]]<-websites
}

press.releases<-unlist(press.list)

press.releases[c(1,2)]

Web Aggregator Example

Step 5: Iterate While Articles Remain

while(posts.remaining > 0){
  counter<- counter + 1
  file.data<-getURL(new.url)
  xml.object<-read_html(file.data)
  
  posts<-xml.object %>%
    html_nodes("post")
  post.index[[counter]]<-do.call("rbind",
                                 lapply(posts, process.post.function))
  
  posts.remaining<-xml.object %>%
    html_node("moreresultsavailable") %>%
    html_text
  next.list<-xml.object %>%
    html_nodes("next") %>%
    html_text
  
  new.url<-paste("https://webhose.io", next.list, sep="")
}

Processing Data: What do we Need?

  • Ngram List (for searching)

    • Example Sentence: "Donald Trump is running for president"

    • bi-gram: Donald Trump; Trump is; is running; running for; for president

    • tri-gram: Donald Trump is; Trump is running; is running for; running for president

    • quad-gram(?): Donald Trump is running; Trump is running for; is running for president

  • Article Index (for visualizing)

Processing Data: Ngram List

Process Article Text into Unique Ngrams (from length 2 to 10):

ngram.function<-function(article.text){
  words.processed<-preprocess(article.text, case="lower", 
                              split.at.punct=TRUE)
  word.block<-concat(words.processed)
  source <- VectorSource(word.block)
  corpus <- Corpus(source)
  Tokenizer <- function(x){
    NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 10))
  }
  tdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(corpus, 
                            control = list(tokenize = Tokenizer, 
                                           removePunctuation = TRUE))
  ngram.vector<-as.vector(tdm$dimnames$Terms)
  return(ngram.vector)
}

Searching Data: Text-Similarity Method

Logic:

  • Input = Phrase, Threshold
    • Filter to ngrams with length = length of phrase (+ or - 1)
    • Score similarity of phrase and filtered ngrams (Jaro-Winkler)
  • Output = phrases with similarity > threshold

Searching Data: Text-Similarity Method

Code:

  phrase = 'ban muslims'
  phrase.words<-length(unlist(strsplit(phrase," ")))
  threshold<- input$matchSlider
      
  candidatePhrase <- Ngram.list.rollup[Ngram.list.rollup$len == 
                                         phrase.words + 1 | 
                                         Ngram.list.rollup$len == 
                                         phrase.words - 1 | 
                                         Ngram.list.rollup$len == 
                                         phrase.words,]
  candidatePhrase$distCalc <-stringdist(phrase, candidatePhrase$x, 
                                        method="jw")
  Close.Matches<-candidatePhrase[candidatePhrase$distCalc < threshold,]
      
  colnames(Close.Matches) <- c("Phrase", "Length", "JaroWinklerDistance")

Searching Data: Text-Similarity Method

Example:

library(stringdist)

searchPhrase <- 'ban muslims'

matchPhrases <- c('bar muslims', 'forbid muslims', 'restrict muslims')

stringdist(searchPhrase, matchPhrases, method="jw")
## [1] 0.06060606 0.29076479 0.42424242

Searching Data: Semantic Matching

Logic:

  • Input = Phrase
    • Look for synonyms for each word in phrase
    • Create all unique combinations of synonyms
    • Search (exact match) for synonym phrases in ngram list
  • Output = synonym phrases that appear in the data

Searching Data: Semantic Matching

Code (pt1):

require(qdap)

phrase <- 'ban muslims'
temp <- list()
for(i in 1:length(words)) {
  if(is.null(synonyms(words[i]))) {
    temp[[i]] <- words[i]
  } else{
    temp[[i]] <- c(words[i],synonyms(words[i], return.list=FALSE))
  }
}

test <- expand.grid(temp[[1]], temp[[2]])

Searching Data: Semantic Matching

Code (pt2):

temp <- NULL
possiblePhrases <- NULL
for(i in 1:nrow(test)){

  for (j in 1:ncol(test)) {
    temp <- paste(temp, as.character(test[i,j]))
    temp <- sub("^\\s+", "", temp)
